Just a regular person. Husband and father of 3. I got into 3D printing in 2017. I love being able to take an idea and make it from scratch, and see it through to completion. I design, document, program/debug, test, fabricate, and build many my of my own devices, electronics, and machines. I do a lot of tinkering with C, C++, and Arduino controllers, steppers, servos, sensors, etc. I find that many off-the-shelf items and solutions nearly always fall short of my expectations, or are just simply not available in the configuration I want or need. I do some amateur photography, nothing to brag about. Experienced with AutoCAD and Inventor. I can solder, braze, and weld. I have a nice lab in my basement where all the magic happens, and where my 3D printer resides. I have a lathe I'm restoring, and I'm working on building a CNC mill.

I have an "Anycubic Delta Linear Plus Kossel Rostock" 3D printer. It has a 240mm diameter build plate and 300mm build height. I've made several modifications to it: I added solid aluminum corners at top and bottom for better rigidity, aluminum upper control arm brackets, a Meanwell 24V 350W (14.6A) power supply for the bed with a TriGorilla MOSFET heating controller to handle the additional power, some custom bed leveling brackets.

That's all you need to know about me right now.

bio:
Hi, I'm Cathal!
I'm a full-time biohacker and a science and computer nerd from Cork, Ireland. I studied Genetics in UCC years back, and have been meandering through an interesting career path since then.

I spent some time pursuing a postgrad in Cancer Research, before switching track entirely and setting up my own synthetic biology lab in a spare bedroom. I have spent the time since working towards making advanced biotechnology into a thing someone can do as a hobby, or by necessity, at low cost and minimal effort.

Part of what started this journey was 3D printing. As I spent time working in a lab and exploring 3D design and manufacture at home, I came to realise that a lot of the cost of laboratory equipment was due to artificial scarcity and not merly because science is innately expensive (it can be, but not always). Electing for proof-by-synthesis, I designed and printed a rotor for a dremel which could be used as a high-speed microcentrifuge, a critical piece of biotechnology equipment.

After this, I started to see science in a whole different light. Even science protocols/methods are more complex than they need to be, and with an engineering mindset primed by design and iteration in 3D printing, and a newfound love for programming, I've since been assembling equipment, protocols and DNA to make things easier for biohackers everywhere.

I don't owe it all to 3D printing, but it certainly started me on an exciting journey that I'm still following.

I'm afraid during this time, I found less and less time to maintain my old printer, so you may note that my designs here are very old; 3D printing itself has fallen by the wayside as I focus more and more on designing DNA. However, I hope for that soon to change, and when it does you'll find my new designs hosted on my Gitorious account, if you like:
https://gitorious.org/~cathalgarvey

Meanwhile, all of my designs and images can safely be assumed CC-SA if they don't say otherwise; most say CC-BY-SA. If you'd like a high-quality print of some of my work, I host a shapeways shop where I sell some lab equipment that might otherwise cost a fortune, and biologically-inspired ornaments only possible through 3D printing:
http://www.shapeways.com/shops/labsfromfabs

Also, I tweet a lot:
@onetruecathal

I'm a Finnish designer living in South-Korea and a co-founder of Almond Studio, an international design studio based in Seoul.
www.almond-studio.com

During my studies I lived many small apartments with a layout weirder than the other. It inspired me to design "moidules", a set of connectors for building flexible shelving systems in any situations.
('Moi!' means 'Hello!' in Finnish.)

I just loved the result, so I decided to share my moidules with the world. Any size, any colour, any where, anytime... You can basically custom make your shelving system to fit any space or need. All you need is a 3D-printer and access to a saw or a laser cutter.

First set of moidules is designed to use with 9mm board (MDF, plywood...). For request I can upload moidules that would fit materials of other thickness. :)

Enjoy!

I spent over 22 years in the IT industry primarily as. Network Architect, but after an injury and increasing boredom , I threw caution to the wind and joined the amazing world of non-profit Aerospace..Yes, I see the puzlesd looks... I started a non-profit space exploration advocacy group, pioneersofspace.org . oriented towards making space accessible and affordable. Primarily the site, launching on eclipse day, is a resource portal for open-source software and open-hardware following the cubesat standard, but focusing on travel, not orbit.

I am launching a 3U cubesat in April, 2018 as a testing platform for a bunch of new concepts, including several pico propulsion concepts which are within launch guidelines and can produce sufficient delta-v. The cube-probe is entirely hand made, even the magnetorques are hand wound.

So, as you guessed, the purpose of a 3d printer is space-craft prototyping. ABS or PLA will never fly, but keeping my eye on Full-Metal Desktop. Being able to print a cubesat frame with the bus built into it would cut down hardware and launch costs.

Anyone interested in helping out on printing spacecraft or any other area is free to contact me as I always welcome free labor :)
